<section xml:id="introduction-to-limits">
<title>Introduction to limits</title>


<paragraphs xml:id="the-plan-6">
<title>The Plan</title>

<p> The next topic, limits of functions, is almost a purely
mathematical topic, but one we will soon use to develop one of the
central concepts of calculus. Imagine yourself working in the lab, about
to undertake an exciting experiment. Before you can dive in, you must
first orient yourself with your equipment, calibrate it, and practice a
few basic techniques. Think of this topic, limits<fn>

<p> Limits are undoubtedly important throughout mathematics
and fill a whole chapter of a typical calculus course. They are central
for many topics in advanced mathematics, but we will take just a brief
look into limits.
</p></fn>, as an orientation to an important piece of
machinery.
</p>
</paragraphs>

<paragraphs xml:id="limits">
<title>Limits</title>

<p>	In addition to <term>eventually</term> allowing us
to compute instantaneous rates of change (derivatives) of mathematical
functions, we use limits to study and describe behavior of functions.
</p>


<paragraphs xml:id="concept-of-a-limit">
<title>Concept of a limit</title>

<p> For a function <m>f(x)</m> and two numbers
<m>a</m> and <m>L</m>, the statement <me>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x) =
L,</me> means that <q>the value of <m>f(x)</m> gets closer and closer to
<m>L</m> as <m>x</m> gets closer and closer to <m>a</m>.</q> Sometimes
we say more simply that <q>the value of <m>f(x)</m> approaches <m>L</m>
as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m>.</q> This helps us explain and compute
<sq>what <m>f(x)</m> does</sq> near a point <m>x=a</m> <term>even if
<m>f(a)</m> is undefined</term>!
</p>

<figure>
<image xml:id="blank-graph-limit-intro" source="graph.png" width = "50%"/>
<caption>A sketch to motivate the idea of limits.</caption>
</figure>

</paragraphs>

<paragraphs xml:id="one-and-twosided-limits">
<title>One– and two–sided limits</title>

<p> Some functions have complicated domains and we
can only discuss what happens as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> from one
side. We say one of the following:
</p>

<figure>
<sidebyside>
<image xml:id="blank-graph-limit-left" source="graph.png" width = "50%"/>
<image xml:id="blank-graph-limit-right" source="graph.png" width = "50%"/>
</sidebyside>
<caption>Talking about limits, a tool for mathematical precision, requires precision in our approach.</caption>
</figure>

<p> Consider the appropriate one–sided and two–sided
limits for the following functions.
</p>

<figure>
<image xml:id="image-graph-limit-signum" source="bas_func_sgn.png" width = "50%"/>
<caption>image</caption>
</figure>

<p> <me>\begin{aligned}
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^-} \operatorname{sgn}(x)=\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^+}\operatorname{sgn}(x)=\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0}\operatorname{sgn}(x)=\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<figure>
<image xml:id="image-graph-limit-identity"  source="bas_func_id.png" width = "50%"/>
<caption>image</caption>
</figure>

<p> <me>\begin{aligned}
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^-}x=\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^+}x=\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0}x=\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<figure>
<image  xml:id="image-graph-limit-constant" source="bas_func_cons.png" width = "50%"/>
<caption>image</caption>
</figure>

<p> <me>\begin{aligned}[t]
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^-}0.64=\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^+}0.64=\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0}0.64=\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-basic-limits">
<title>Limits of basic functions</title>
<statement><p>
Consider limits of the following
two basic functions.

<ol>
<li> <p> Suppose <m>f(x)=c</m>, where <m>c</m> is a
constant, for all <m>x</m>. Then for any value of <m>a</m>
<me>\lim_{x\to a}f(x) = \lim_{x\to a}c=c,</me> or, in words <em>the
limit of a constant function is that value of that constant as <m>x</m>
approaches any value</em>.</p> </li>
<li> <p> Suppose <m>f(x)=x</m> for all <m>x</m>. Then for
any value of <m>a</m> <me>\lim_{x\to a}f(x)=\lim_{x\to a} x =a,</me> or,
in words<em>values of the the function <m>x</m> approach <m>a</m> as the
variable <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m></em>.</p> </li>

</ol>
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<p> Consider the appropriate one–sided and two–sided
limits for the following functions.
</p>

<p> <image  xml:id="image-graph-limit-signum-more" source='bas_func_sgn.png' width = "50%"/> Limits at <m>x=0</m>,
<me>\begin{aligned}
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^-} \operatorname{sgn}(x)=-1\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^+}\operatorname{sgn}(x)=1\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0}\operatorname{sgn}(x)=~\text{DNE}\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<p> Limits at a negative value, <me>\begin{aligned}
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow-0.5^-} \operatorname{sgn}(x)=-1\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow-0.5^+}\operatorname{sgn}(x)=-1\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow-0.5}\operatorname{sgn}(x)=-1\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<p> Limits at a positive value, <me>\begin{aligned}
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0.5^-} \operatorname{sgn}(x)=1\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0.5^+}\operatorname{sgn}(x)=1\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0.5}\operatorname{sgn}(x)=1\\\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<figure>
<image  xml:id="image-graph-limit-identity-more"  source="bas_func_id.png" width = "50%"/>
<caption>image</caption>
</figure>

<p> Limits at <m>x=0</m>, <me>\begin{aligned}
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^-}x=0\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^+}x=0\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0}x=0\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<p> Limits at a negative value, <me>\begin{aligned}
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow-0.5^-}x=-0.5\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow-0.5^+}x=-0.5\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow-0.5}x=-0.5\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<p> Limits at a positive value, <me>\begin{aligned}
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0.5^-}x=0.5\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0.5^+}x=0.5\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0.5}x=0.5\\\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<figure>
<image  xml:id="image-graph-limit-constant-more" source="bas_func_cons.png" width = "50%"/>
<caption>image</caption>
</figure>

<p> Limits at <m>x=0</m>, <me>\begin{aligned}
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^-}0.64=0.64\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0^+}0.64=0.64\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0}0.64=0.64\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<p> Limits at a negative value, <me>\begin{aligned}
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow-0.5^-}0.64=0.64\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow-0.5^+}0.64=0.64\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow-0.5}0.64=0.64\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<p> Limits at a positive value, <me>\begin{aligned}
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0.5^-}0.64=0.64\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0.5^+}0.64=0.64\\
&amp;\lim_{x\rightarrow0.5}0.64=0.64\\\end{aligned}</me>
</p>

<p> Notice that the only (two-sided) limit to not
exist is the one that corresponds to the most complicated of the three
graphs in its most complicated portion (left panel: near <m>x=0</m>).
This is because the one-sided limits of the <m>\operatorname{sgn(x)}</m>
function do not match as <m>x</m> approaches <m>0</m> from the left and
right. In all other cases we are looking at graphs that <sq>look more
familiar</sq> (no jumps, no open or filled points) at the points we are
evaluating the limits. Also notice that
</p>

<p><ul>
<li> <p> we can say things like <m>x\to-0.5^+</m> which
refers to our attempt to approach the <m>x</m> value of <m>-0.5</m> from
the right hand side.</p> </li>
<li> <p> the superscript has nothing to do with the sign
of the number itself, only the direction from which we approach the
number.</p> </li>

</ul></p>

<p> We will spend most of our time looking at
two-sided limits once we get an understanding of some important
categories of functions.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-combining-limits">
<title>limits of combinations of functions</title>
<statement><p>
Suppose <m>f(x)</m> and
<m>g(x)</m> are functions with well-defined limits at <m>x=a</m>.

<ol>
<li> <p> The limit of the sum is the sum of the limits
<me>\lim_{x\to a}\big[ f(x)+g(x)\big]=\lim_{x\to a} f(x) + \lim_{x\to a}
g(x)</me></p> </li>
<li> <p> The limit of the product is the product of the
limits <me>\lim_{x\to a}\big[ f(x)g(x)\big]=\big[\lim_{x\to a} f(x)\big]
\cdot \big[\lim_{x\to a} g(x)\big]</me></p> </li>
<li> <p> The limit of a constant times a function is the
constant times the limit of the function <me>\lim_{x\to a}\big[
cf(x)\big]=c\cdot \lim_{x\to a} f(x)</me></p> </li>
<li> <p> Provided <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a} g(x) \ne
0</m>, the limit of the quotient (or ratio) is the quotient (or ratio)
of the limits <me>\lim_{x\to a}\left(
\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\right)=\frac{\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a}
f(x)}{\displaystyle\lim_{x\to a} g(x)}.</me></p> </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>


<paragraphs xml:id="polynomials">
<title>Polynomials</title>

<p> Since a polynomial (e.g., a quadratic or a cubic
function) is the sum of terms that involve variables (like <m>x</m>) to
powers (like <m>x^{2}</m>) multiplied by constants (like <m>3x^{2}</m>),
we could decompose limits of polynomials using <xref
ref="thm-combining-limits" /> and evaluate them with <xref
ref="thm-basic-limits" />.
</p>
</paragraphs>

